Task 1: Set Up Key-Based Authentication for SSH
Subtask 1.1: Generate SSH Key Pair
First, we'll create a new SSH key pair for secure authentication.

Open a terminal and check if you already have SSH keys:
ls -la ~/.ssh/
Generate a new SSH key pair using RSA encryption with 4096 bits:
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"
Follow the prompts:

Press Enter to accept the default file location (/home/username/.ssh/id_rsa)
Enter a strong passphrase when prompted (recommended for security)
Confirm the passphrase
Verify the key generation:

ls -la ~/.ssh/
You should see two files:

id_rsa (private key)
id_rsa.pub (public key)
Subtask 1.2: Set Up Key-Based Authentication
Create a second user account to test SSH authentication:
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash testuser
sudo passwd testuser
Switch to the testuser account:
sudo su - testuser
Create the .ssh directory for the testuser:
mkdir -p ~/.ssh
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
Exit back to your original user:
exit
Copy your public key to the testuser's authorized_keys file:
sudo cp ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub /home/testuser/.ssh/authorized_keys
sudo chown testuser:testuser /home/testuser/.ssh/authorized_keys
sudo chmod 600 /home/testuser/.ssh/authorized_keys
Subtask 1.3: Test Key-Based Authentication
Test SSH connection using keys:
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa testuser@localhost
If prompted for the passphrase, enter it and verify you can log in without a password.

Exit the SSH session:

exit
Task 2: Harden SSH Configurations
Subtask 2.1: Backup Original SSH Configuration
Create a backup of the original SSH configuration:
sudo cp /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.backup
View the current configuration:
sudo cat /etc/ssh/sshd_config | grep -E "^[^#]"
Subtask 2.2: Disable Root Login
Edit the SSH configuration file:
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Find and modify the following line (or add it if it doesn't exist):
PermitRootLogin no
Add additional security settings:
# Disable password authentication (force key-based auth)
PasswordAuthentication no
PubkeyAuthentication yes
AuthorizedKeysFile .ssh/authorized_keys

# Disable empty passwords
PermitEmptyPasswords no

# Disable X11 forwarding if not needed
X11Forwarding no

# Set login grace time
LoginGraceTime 60

# Maximum authentication attempts
MaxAuthTries 3

# Allow specific users only
AllowUsers testuser yourusername
Subtask 2.3: Change SSH Port
In the same configuration file, find the Port line and change it:
Port 2222
Save and exit the editor (Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter for nano).
Subtask 2.4: Apply Configuration Changes
Test the configuration for syntax errors:
sudo sshd -t
If no errors, restart the SSH service:
sudo systemctl restart sshd
Verify the service is running:
sudo systemctl status sshd
Check if SSH is listening on the new port:
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep :2222
Subtask 2.5: Test Hardened SSH Configuration
Test SSH connection on the new port:
ssh -p 2222 -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa testuser@localhost
Verify root login is disabled (this should fail):
ssh -p 2222 root@localhost
Exit the test session:
exit
Task 3: Manage SSH Keys with ssh-agent
Subtask 3.1: Start and Configure ssh-agent
Start ssh-agent in the background:
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
Verify ssh-agent is running:
echo $SSH_AGENT_PID
ps aux | grep ssh-agent
Subtask 3.2: Add SSH Keys to ssh-agent
Add your private key to ssh-agent:
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa
Enter your passphrase when prompted.

List keys currently managed by ssh-agent:

ssh-add -l
Test SSH connection without entering passphrase:
ssh -p 2222 testuser@localhost
You should now connect without being prompted for the passphrase.

Exit the SSH session:
exit
Subtask 3.3: Create SSH Agent Startup Script
Create a script to automatically start ssh-agent:
nano ~/.ssh/ssh-agent-startup.sh
Add the following content:
#!/bin/bash

# SSH Agent startup script
SSH_ENV="$HOME/.ssh/environment"

function start_agent {
    echo "Initializing new SSH agent..."
    /usr/bin/ssh-agent | sed 's/^echo/#echo/' > "${SSH_ENV}"
    echo succeeded
    chmod 600 "${SSH_ENV}"
    . "${SSH_ENV}" > /dev/null
    /usr/bin/ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa;
}

# Source SSH settings, if applicable
if [ -f "${SSH_ENV}" ]; then
    . "${SSH_ENV}" > /dev/null
    ps -ef | grep ${SSH_AGENT_PID} | grep ssh-agent$ > /dev/null || {
        start_agent;
    }
else
    start_agent;
fi
Make the script executable:
chmod +x ~/.ssh/ssh-agent-startup.sh
Add to your shell profile:
echo "source ~/.ssh/ssh-agent-startup.sh" >> ~/.bashrc
Subtask 3.4: Advanced SSH Key Management
Generate additional SSH keys for different purposes:
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_github -C "github_key"
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -f ~/.ssh/id_rsa_server -C "server_key"
Create SSH config file for key management:
nano ~/.ssh/config
Add configuration for different hosts:
# Default configuration
Host *
    AddKeysToAgent yes
    UseKeychain yes
    IdentitiesOnly yes

# Local server configuration
Host localhost
    HostName localhost
    Port 2222
    User testuser
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa

# GitHub configuration example
Host github.com
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_github

# Server configuration example
Host myserver
    HostName localhost
    Port 2222
    User testuser
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa_server
Set proper permissions:
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config
Subtask 3.5: Test Advanced Key Management
Add all keys to ssh-agent:
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_github
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa_server
List all loaded keys:
ssh-add -l
Test connection using SSH config:
ssh localhost
Remove specific key from agent:
ssh-add -d ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_github
Remove all keys from agent:
ssh-add -D
Verification and Testing
Security Verification Checklist
Verify SSH hardening settings:
sudo sshd -T | grep -E "(permitrootlogin|passwordauthentication|port|maxauthtries)"
Check SSH service status:
sudo systemctl status sshd
sudo ss -tlnp | grep :2222
Test security measures:
# This should fail (root login disabled)
ssh -p 2222 root@localhost

# This should work (key-based auth)
ssh -p 2222 testuser@localhost
Verify ssh-agent functionality:
ssh-add -l
echo $SSH_AGENT_PID
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Permission Denied (publickey)
Solution:

# Check file permissions
ls -la ~/.ssh/
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa
chmod 644 ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
Issue 2: SSH Agent Not Working
Solution:

# Kill existing agents
pkill ssh-agent

# Start new agent
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"

# Add keys
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa
Issue 3: Connection Refused on New Port
Solution:

# Check if SSH is listening
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep :2222

# Check firewall settings
sudo ufw status
sudo ufw allow 2222/tcp

# Restart SSH service
sudo systemctl restart sshd
Issue 4: Configuration Syntax Errors
Solution:

# Test configuration
sudo sshd -t

# Restore backup if needed
sudo cp /etc/ssh/sshd_config.backup /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Security Best Practices Summary
Always use key-based authentication instead of passwords
Disable root login via SSH
Change default SSH port to reduce automated attacks
Use strong passphrases for SSH keys
Regularly rotate SSH keys and remove unused ones
Monitor SSH logs for suspicious activity
Use ssh-agent to manage keys securely
Set appropriate file permissions for SSH files
Limit user access with AllowUsers directive
Keep SSH software updated regularly
Conclusion
In this lab, you have successfully implemented comprehensive SSH security measures including:

Key-based authentication setup that eliminates password-based vulnerabilities
SSH server hardening through configuration changes that disable root login and change default ports
Advanced key management using ssh-agent for secure and convenient key handling
These security implementations are crucial for protecting Linux systems in production environments. SSH is often the primary entry point for system administration, making its security configuration one of the most important aspects of Linux system hardening.

The skills you've developed in this lab directly apply to real-world scenarios where secure remote access is essential. Key-based authentication, proper SSH hardening, and effective key management are fundamental practices that every Linux administrator must master to maintain secure and reliable systems.

Remember to regularly review and update your SSH configurations, monitor access logs, and follow the principle of least privilege when granting SSH access to users. These practices will help ensure your systems remain secure against evolving security threats.
